To save text to a local file in a JavaScript web app, you can use the `window.open()` method with the "save as" option and provide the URL of the file you want to save. Here's an example:

```javascript
function saveTextToFile(text) {
  var link = document.createElement("a");
  link.href = "data:text/plain;charset=utf-8," + encodeURIComponent(text);
  link.download = "myfile.txt";
  link.click();
}
```

This function takes a string `text` as input and saves it to a file with the name "myfile.txt" in the user's download folder. The `encodeURIComponent()` function is used to encode special characters in the text, so that they can be properly saved to the file.

Note that this method only works for saving text data, not binary data such as images or audio files. Additionally, some browsers may block the "save as" option if the user has disabled it in their browser settings. In those cases, you may need to provide an alternative way for the user to download the file, such as providing a link to a server-side script that generates and sends the file to the user's browser.
